Poll Responses Response: Gibbs sampling would not work well because its probability mass is narrowly condensed within a limited region. For Gibbs sampling, we start with the current state x(t), and x(t) is sampled from a conditional density P(x|y) with y fixed to y(t). A sample y is then sampled from the conditional density P(y|x), using the new value of x. It is very unlikely for us to sample from the region of the target distribution using the conditional densities, meaning that Gibbs sampling will not work well. Further, as the distribution itself is narrow, it might be diffcult to navigate through iterations.

Poll Responses Response: We use the evidence procedure when we want to optimize the hyperparameters, but the integral for optimizing the hyperparameters is too difficult to do. To optimize hyperparameters, we ideally need to use the integral(P(D|hyper)P(hyper)). To get P(D|hyper) we need to marginalize out the weights, which is fine. However, it is difficult to marginalize out the *hyperparameters. Instead of doing this, we use a sort of point estimate for the hyperparameters (i.e. the maximum likelihood estimate, rather than using the entire distribution of hyperparameters). So we do P(D|hyper*)P(hyper*).

Poll Responses Response: In the first case, my model for performance would be a dynamic programming solution, as suggested by Chao. It's a variation on a knapsack problem - how many questions to answer (items) can I fit into a time period (bag), given that they carry differnt costs and rewards. Given unlimited time, the order doesn't matter at all, just my expectation of the probability I can answer the question correctly - if P(correct) * payoff > penalty, I answer the current question. If not, I move onto the next one. Thus, the same strategy isn't rational, as it doesn't necesarily maximize my expected utility.

Poll Responses Response:
The failurs of maximum likelihood methods, or in other words, things that go wrong when you have an improper prior. Without any constraints, if we have a cluster with a mean at a certain point, the likelihood of this point will increase unboundedly as we shrink the variance - mathematically, if x ~ N(x, \sigma^), lim_{\sigma^ \to } P(x) = \infty. This is Not Good™.

One fix is to set a prior on the covariance matrices - Wishart in the general case, or Gamma if we're happy with diagonal covariances. Otherwise, constrain the product of eigenvalues (det(S)) to be above some value.

Arrows in a p.g.m. represent "influence," so that given a directed edge, the probability of the target node is conditional on the source node. Poll Responses Response: The likelihood, L(parameters; data), is equivalent to P(data; parameters). The latter formulation is a probability distribution because it returns the 'probability' (a number) of observing the data given some parameters. The likelihood, on the other hand, is the formulation we use to track down the optimal parameters of a specified model that best describes the data. The model that we choose is probably wrong. However, we can parameterize it in such a way that is close to the truth. Likelihood is one measure of how well our model is parameterized.
